Small-medium unit, mostly sheep-size, some larger taxa. Quite fragmented, but phalanges still whole. Fairly even body part distribution for sheep-size, at least. Relatively little rib, vertebra, or cranial, except for sheep/goat teeth. These are mostly incisors; might they have sifted down from the mandibles in 2600? Note that there is postcranial pig (ulna). Part of a large sheep/goat horn core, poorly preserved. Preservation is variable, but much bone is light in color and chalky in texture; because close to surface or exposed before burial? Cattle humerus and femur seem notably more weathered than the rest; different origin or different cooking practice? Some low temperature burning, mostly on sheep-size limbs; not from roasting, more likely falling or being thrown into fire post-consumption. Some digestion, little or no gnawing. Not a lot of integrity: nothing fits together. Seems like household waste, perhaps not particularly rapid deposition, things getting moved around. Does the relative lack of ribs and vertebrae result from meat sharing? Or are they discarded elsewhere at a different stage of consumption, e.g. before marrow processing? Last number = 139
SCANNED FOR C14, 6/8/12, NIL SUITABLE

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
